ğŸŒ— Dark Mode Setup with TailwindCSS

This project demonstrates how to implement dark mode in two different ways using TailwindCSS:

1ï¸âƒ£ Apply Theme Based on Operating System

If you want the theme to follow the userâ€™s OS preference (system light/dark setting), simply add the dark class in your Tailwind config or HTML.
Tailwind will automatically respect the system preference.

<html class="dark">
  <!-- Your content -->
</html>

2ï¸âƒ£ Allow Users to Choose the Theme

If you want to give users control over the theme (manual toggle), follow these steps:

ğŸ”¹ Step 1: Overwrite the Default dark Variant

In your input.css, add the following line to allow dark mode to apply via a dark class on the <html> element:

@custom-variant dark (&:where(.dark, .dark *));

ğŸ”¹ Step 2: Toggle Dark/Light Mode with JavaScript

Use JavaScript to dynamically add or remove the dark class from the <html> element.

Example:

const html = document.documentElement;

// Enable Dark Mode
html.classList.add("dark");

// Enable Light Mode
html.classList.remove("dark");

// Toggle Mode
html.classList.toggle("dark");


âœ… Now you can either:

Let the theme follow the operating systemâ€™s setting, or

Allow the user to switch manually between light and dark modes.